                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">This started out as a simple answer to a question asked on our guild boards, but after typing it out, I realised that with some editing it could make a useful article for a lot of people. I need some clarifications on a few points, and someone to kick me in the face if I have some of the info wrong. Here the post from the guild boards in it's original form:
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Blah, I go away for two days and you start discussing game mechanics. Spoilsports! Well, here we go: 
<br />

<br />
There are 4 components in mana regen, that I can think of at the moment. 
<br />

<br />
Component 1 - Worn mana regen: The absolute maximum WORN mana regen you can have is 15 mana per tick. This is a hard cap. This used to include a bunch of effects, with FT being the most common, but now it's all called "mana regeneration" on items. All items of this type will add up until you reach the limit at 15. 
<br />
Tribute DOES count as worn mana regen, the tribute effects are added to a "hidden" inventory slot. 
<br />
Koadic's Heightened Focus (the emp robe effect) and a few other similar effects DO NOT count as worn mana regen, because they are actually clicky effects that take up a buff slot. 
<br />

<br />
Component 2 - Mana regen from buffs: For buffs, there is no hard cap. The only limit here is stacking, so the more mana regen buffs you can get on, the better. I believe the current maximum in the game (not counting necros, who are special) would be: 
<br />
C5 (18 in slot 2) 
<br />
Pot9 (8 in slot 4) 
<br />
SD (9 in slot 5) 
<br />
Bard song (22 in shortbuffslot 2) 
<br />
Maelin's Methodical Mind (8 in slot 8 - Quarm shawl effect, higher version of emp robe effect) 
<br />
Allegiant Familiar (8 in slot 12 - wizards only) 
<br />
Force Shield (2 in slot 6 - wizards and necros only) 
<br />
(and the following which are very temporary, but also stack) 
<br />
Paragon of Spirit (80 in slot 10) 
<br />
Mind Wrack (75 in slot 7) 
<br />
Scryer's Trespass (50 in slot 1 - enchanters only) 
<br />
I don't have anything in some slots here, so there may be a few more that stack. I skipped a few class specifics also, only mentioned three of the most significant ones. Wizards will in other words have the maximum of long term "Buff mana regen" (not counting filthy necros) at 18+8+9+22+8+8+2=75 per tick. 
<br />

<br />
Component 3 - Natural mana regen: This has no hard cap either. This is originally 3 per tick standing (and sitting, I believe, if you dont have meditate) at 65. With MC3, you can get this 3 higher. That's right, MC3 adds to your natural mana regen, so doesn't interfere with anything else. Apparently bards can get MC4 in some way to reach 7 per tick. (NOTE: I thought it was 1 per tick standing at 65 without AAs, but I will trust the bard on this, they know this far better than casters) 
<br />

<br />
Component 4 - Meditation: Since about 2001, casters now always meditate while sitting down. The mana gain from meditation is the result of a formula which is "[Meditation skill]/10" rounded down. In other words, at 250 meditation skill, you get 25 mana per tick from meditating. This stacks with all other forms of mana regen. The reason horses/lizards increase your mana regen is that while riding, you count as sitting (with two exceptions), and thus meditating at all times. This has a HUGE effect when casting spells like CH and other long cast spells, as you will still be meditating while casting. For tight CH rotations, a horse will help immensely. There are two occasions where using the horse will stop counting as meditating, and those are: 
<br />
1. Auto-attack ON. 
<br />
2. Moving 
<br />
If you do either of those things, you will not be getting the additional meditation regen. 
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
This helps explain why some highly geared casters never bother to sit at all. Imagine a 65 wiz with all AAs and quarm shawl and fully buffed (with bard) - He will have 6 + 75 + 15 = 96 mana per tick standing, and 121 per tick meditating - not a huge difference. With spells like Harvest and Harvest of Druzzil, the effect is further diminished. Still, for most people at our level - esp not raidbuffed, sitting as often as possible will help a lot.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Anything I present here as being unsure of needs confirmation, and any other errors would be great if pointed out. If someone feels like completing the list of temporary and class specific mana regen spells, that would be cool too. Note that this article will be aimed at the 65 enchanter, not lower level chars.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><center><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=2212" target="_blank" class="postlink"><img src="http://www.elerion.net/pics/sjhosig.jpg" border="0" /></a><span style="font-style: italic"><span style="font-size: 9px; line-height: normal">
<br />
"Carrot Cake Soup is like the taste of watching girls make out. It has an extraordinary power that oscillates between gentle and overwhelming, between light and dark, between pleasure and more pleasure." - Penny Arcade</span></span></center></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
